passages.text: Despite relatively quiet AI demand for China data centers due to supply bottleneck in 2Q25 as expected (e.g. GDS 40MW hyperscale orders vs. 152MW in 1Q25, VNET 20MW wholesale orders vs. 123MW in 1Q25), GDS and VNET (both Buy rated) delivered above- expected revenue and EBITDA (see our first takes for GDS and VNET) driven by solid customer move- in pace and resilient pricing, which in our view reflect their discipline in taking quality orders and delivering new capacity. This contrasts with Sinnet (Sell)'s 2Q25 soft results (revenue/EBITDA \(3\% /1\%\) below GSe) reflecting continued divergence between data center operators that can capture the growing AI/cloud demand and those more exposed to traditional retail demand which remains lukewarm.

We believe the next few months will be critical to watch in terms of order volume recovery for China AI infrastructure. As Nvidia is working with the US government to obtain approvals to sell Blackwell- based products in China which is "a real possibility" as per Nvidia, we expect potentially increased new order volume toward 2025- end or early 2026 if such chip variants receive approvals from the US and China.

Specifically, we note: i) for GDS China, management tone is shifting from prior deleveraging focused to now growth- oriented i.e. more active capex spending to shorten lead time (similar to VNET), in the context of successful execution to bring its net debt/adj. EBITDA (based on last quarter annualized to 6.1x as of Jun 2025 or 5.7x after the C- REIT listing; ii) for VNET, management remains committed to Rmb2bn net proceeds for the rest of 2025 from private REIT issuance, indicated potential for another 2025 revenue/EBITDA guidance raise if customers' move- in pace stays on track, and reiterated long- term goal to grow the capacity of assets under management to 40GW in the next decade.

Moving to the broader APAC data center space, DayOne (36% owned by GDS) delivered in- line revenue and above- expected adj. EBITDA, \(+144\% / + 156\%\) yoy respectively. We believe DayOne as of Jun 2025 reached a few milestones: i) with 224MW live capacity, DayOne has become the largest data center operator in the SIJORI with 215MW live capacity (Exhibit 11), followed by 128MW by AirTrunk

(Private, as per DC Byte); ii) with 783MW committed capacity including anchor orders in Thailand and Finland in 2Q25, DayOne is rapidly approaching the 800MW+ committed capacity of AirTrunk as of Sep 2024 when it was acquired by Blackstone at US\(15.7bn enterprise value (incl. capex for committed projects) despite different regional mix; iii) compared to regional listed peers, DayOne surpassed NEXTDC (NXT.AX, covered by Kane Hannan, CFA, Buy) on live capacity and revenue (Exhibit 12, Exhibit 13), with almost twice utilized capacity which may be almost doubled over the next 6- 9 months, yet still lagged behind on EBITDA and unit economics (e.g. MSR and EBITDA per MW on Exhibit 15).

That said, we acknowledge policy uncertainties (e.g. new power tariffs in Malaysia from Jul) and rising competition in APAC (e.g. Bridge Data Centres raising US\(2.8bn debt in Mar for Malaysia/Thailand expansion, DayOne raising c.US\)4bn debt in Jun for SIJORI expansion, AirTrunk closing US\)10.4bn debt refinancing in Aug), which appears to have discouraged late comers being new entrants (e.g. Sinnet).

We reiterate our Buy ratings on GDS Holdings (GDS/9698.HK) with our 12m SOTP- based target price raised to US\(42/HK\)41 (vs. US\)40/HK\)39 prior), and VNET Group (VNET) with our 12m EV/EBITDA- based target price raised to US\(13 (vs. US\)12 prior), and stay Sell on Sinnet (300383.SZ).

We factor in the completion of C- REIT listing in Aug 2025; as we wrote earlier, GDS has deconsolidated 29MW (or 13ksqm as per GSe) of capacity and Rmb175mn/Rmb144mn of revenue/EBITDA, representing \(2\%\) of revenue and \(3\%\) adj. EBITDA in 2025E (as per prior GSe), and received c.Rmb1.6bn proceeds net of re- investments. We expect the net debt/LTM EBITDA of GDS to decline to 5.7x in 3Q25E (vs. \(6.1x\) in 2Q25).

Reflecting GDS' 2Q25 results (see GS first take), we keep our 2025- 27E revenue and adj. EBITDA forecasts for GDS China largely unchanged, primarily on \(2 - 3\%\) lower area utilized due to C- REITs deconsolidation, offset by modestly higher MSR assumptions. While for DayOne, we raise 2025- 27E revenue forecasts by \(1 - 15\%\) , and raise adj. EBITDA forecasts by \(15 - 23\%\) on above- expected capacity delivery and EBITDA margin ramp- up.
Our target prices are based on SOTP valuation (unchanged) in which we apply: 1) 14.5x target EV/EBITDA to GDS China's 2026E EBITDA; 2) 21x target EV/EBITDA to DayOne's

2026E EBITDA, adjusted by the \(35.6\%\) stake owned by GDS (unchanged); 3) \(10\%\) holdco. discount (unchanged). Our 12-month target prices for GDS/9698.HK are revised to US\(42/HK\)41 (from US\)40/HK\(39 prior). Stay Buy with 26\%/20\% upside potential for GDS/9698.HK.

GDS is the leader in China's carrier- neutral data center market with a wholesale- centric business model. We are constructive on GDS's roadmap for its China and international

businesses, and believe it is well positioned to capture demand- alpha from Generative AI- driven cloud growth acceleration (especially for AI inferencing) and overseas expansion. For GDS China, we believe the focus on backlog delivery will lead to higher revenue growth visibility, EBITDA/FCF improvement. For DayOne, as it becomes a standalone business with a different growth/profitability profile, we see strong contract move- in visibility in the near- term and continued capacity expansion in the mid- term.

Reflecting VNET's 2Q25 results (see GS first take), we raise our 2025- 27E revenue by \(5 - 6\%\) and adj. EBITDA by \(3 - 4\%\) primarily driven by \(11 - 15\%\) higher wholesale IDC revenue on faster- than- expected move- in. Our revised 2025E revenue and adj. EBITDA are both \(5\%\) above the updated guidance at the midpoint; in other words, we see potential for the company to further raise full- year guidance, as the guidance implies only \(2 - 7\%\) yoy revenue/adj. EBITDA growth in 2H25E after we factor in 2Q25 results (vs. GSe of \(16\% /14\%\) yoy revenue/adj. EBITDA growth in 2H25E).
Accordingly, our 12m EV/EBITDA- based TP is revised to US\(13.0 (vs. US\)12.0 prior), based on a target 12m- fwd EV/EBITDA multiple of 12x applied to 2026E EBITDA (unchanged). Maintain Buy.

VNET is China's leading carrier- neutral data center operator and derived c.74% of its 2024 revenue from IDCs vs. c.26% from cloud computing and VAS. We see VNET transforming itself from a traditional retail IDC operator to a fast- growing wholesale IDC

operator and entering a revenue/EBITDA growth acceleration phase over the next few years from intensifying AI investment, with wholesale IDC growing at \(52 - 55\%\) revenue/EBITDA CAGRs in 2024- 27E. We believe rising wholesale IDC revenue/EBITDA contributions should lead to continued upward multiple re- rating and valuation compounding for VNET. We are Buy rated.

2025 results takeaway- 2Q25 results: Sinnet reported mixed 2Q25 results. Revenue declined \(- 3\%\) yoy to Rmb1.9bn (3% below GSe yet 3% above VA consensus), with inline IDC revenue (flat yoy) and cloud computing revenue (- 4% yoy revenue) dragged by other revenue. EBITDA came inline at 13% yoy to Rmb348mn (GSe), or 8% above consensus. Net income declined - 56% yoy to Rmb46mn (- 63%/- 57% below GSe or consensus), on higher non- operating expenses due to asset disposal of cloud computing business.

IDC business: IDC cabinets in service grew to 72k in 2Q25 (vs. 59k in 1Q25), primarily from the Tianjin project contribution. That said, management commented that H20 chip restriction has delayed the customer move- in in 1H25, and sees uncertainty for the move- in timing, which depends on the supply of B30 or other domestic chips.

We lower 2025E revenue by 2% on below- expected utilization of IDC business on slower move- in this year, and keep EBITDA largely unchanged. We keep 2026- 27E revenue largely unchanged on: i) 3- 7% higher IDC revenue due to above- expected capacity delivery in 1H25 which could see faster move- in in 2026- 27E, yet ii) offset by lower cloud computing and other revenue. We raise EBITDA in 2026- 27E by 4- 6%.
We raise our 12m- fwd EV/EBITDA based target price for Sinnet to Rmb11.4 (vs.

Rmb10.5 prior), as we: i) apply a higher EV/EBITDA multiple of 16.1x (vs. 15.5x prior) benchmarking 1-year-average of its 12m-fwd EV/EBITDA; and ii) roll over the valuation to 2025-end (vs. mid-2025 prior), which is now in line with GDS/VNET. Stay Sell as we believe its valuation is less attractive vs. peers based on EV/EBITDA related to growth outlook, and the company appears to be off-cycle in the context of rising AI/cloud hyperscaler demand.

Sinnet Technology is China's leading carrier- neutral IDC operator, deriving c.30% revenue in 2024 from IDC vs. c.70% from cloud computing (including AWS Beijing and marketing SaaS). While a flexible construction schedule based on customers' move- in pace helps maintain stable utilization, Sinnet has been losing market share in the China IDC market over the past years. We believe soft demand and pricing pressure will affect IDC revenue growth and see limited demand alpha generation vs. peers. We are Sell rated on Sinnet as we await more certainty on demand recovery and capacity delivery schedule for its IDC business, and see its new initiatives (e.g. AIDC and overseas)

remaining in an investment stage. We also believe its valuation is less attractive vs. peers based on EV/EBITDA related to growth outlook, and the company appears to be off- cycle in the context of rising AI/cloud hyperscaler demand.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FC and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
